\par Mr. and Mrs. Dursley, of number four, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Privet Drive{\*\xmlclose}, were proud to say that they were perfectly normal, thank you very much. They were the last people you\rquote d expect to be in\-
volved in anything strange or mysterious, because they just didn\rquote t hold with such nonsense.
\par Mr. Dursley was the director of a firm called Grunnings, which made drills. He was a big, beefy man with hardly any neck, al\-though h
e did have a very large mustache. Mrs. Dursley was thin and blonde and had nearly twice the usual amount of neck, which came in very useful as she spent so much of her time craning over garden fences, spying on the neighbors. The Dursleys had a small son 
called {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dudley{\*\xmlclose} and in their opinion there was no finer boy any\-where.
\par The Dursleys had everything they wanted, but they also had a secret, and their greatest fear was that somebody would discover it. They didn\rquote t think they could bear it if anyone found out about the Potters. Mrs. Potter was Mrs. Dursley\rquote 
s sister, but they hadn\rquote t met for several years; in fact, Mrs. Dursley pretended she didn\rquote t have a sister, because her sister and her good-for-nothing husband were as unDursleyish as it was possible to be. The
 Dursleys shuddered to think what the neighbors would say if the Potters arrived in the street. The Dursleys knew that the Potters had a small son, too, but they had never even seen him. This boy was another good reason for keeping the Potters away; they 
didn\rquote t want {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dudley{\*\xmlclose} mixing with a child like that.
\par When Mr. and Mrs. Dursley woke up on the dull, gray Tuesday our story starts, there was nothing about the cloudy sky outside to suggest that strange and mysterious things would soon be happen\-ing all over th
e country. Mr. Dursley hummed as he picked out his most boring tie for work, and Mrs. Dursley gossiped away happily as she wrestled a screaming {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dudley{\*\xmlclose} into his high chair.
\par None of them noticed a large, tawny owl flutter past the window.
\par At half past eight, Mr. Dursley picked up his briefcase, pecked Mrs. Dursley on the cheek, and tried to kiss Dudley good-bye but missed, because {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dudley{\*\xmlclose}
 was now having a tantrum and throwing his cereal at the walls. \'93Little tyke,\'94 chortled Mr. Dursley as he left the house. He got into his car and backed out of number four\rquote s drive.
\par It was on the corner of the street that he noticed the first sign of something peculiar \emdash  a cat reading a map. For a second, Mr. Dursley didn\rquote t realize what he had seen \emdash  then he jerked his head arou
nd to look again. There was a tabby cat standing on the corner of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Privet Drive{\*\xmlclose}, but there wasn\rquote 
t a map in sight. What could he have been thinking of? It must have been a trick of the light. Mr. Dursley blinked and stared at the cat. It stared back. As Mr. Durs\-
ley drove around the corner and up the road, he watched the cat in his mirror. It was now reading the sign that said {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Privet Drive{\*\xmlclose} \emdash  no, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\lang1033\langfe3081\langnp1033\insrsid12529987\charrsid12529987 looking}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang1033\langfe3081\langnp1033\insrsid12529987\charrsid12529987  at the sign; cats couldn\rquote t read maps }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\lang1033\langfe3081\langnp1033\insrsid12529987\charrsid12529987 or}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang1033\langfe3081\langnp1033\insrsid12529987\charrsid12529987  signs. Mr. Dursley gave himself a little shake and put the cat out 
of his mind. As he drove toward town he thought of nothing except a large order of drills he was hoping to get that day.
\par But on the edge of town, drills were driven out of his mind by something else. As he sat in the usual morning traffic jam, he couldn\rquote t 
help noticing that there seemed to be a lot of strangely dressed people about. People in cloaks. Mr. Dursley couldn\rquote t bear people who dressed in funny clothes \emdash 
 the getups you saw on young people! He supposed this was some stupid new fashion. He drummed his fingers on the steering wheel and his eyes fell on a huddle of these weirdos standing quite close by. They were whis\-
pering excitedly together. Mr. Dursley was enraged to see that a couple of them weren\rquote t young at all; why, that man had to be older than 
he was, and wearing an emerald-green cloak! The nerve of him! But then it struck Mr. Dursley that this was probably some silly stunt \emdash  these people were obviously collecting for some\-thing }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang1033\langfe3081\langnp1033\insrsid12007620 \'85}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang1033\langfe3081\langnp1033\insrsid12529987\charrsid12529987  yes, that would be it. The traffic moved on and a few minutes lat
er, Mr. Dursley arrived in the Grunnings parking lot, his mind back on drills.
\par Mr. Dursley always sat with his back to the window in his office on the ninth floor. If he hadn\rquote t, he might have found it harder to concentrate on drills that morning. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\lang1033\langfe3081\langnp1033\insrsid12529987\charrsid12529987 He}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang1033\langfe3081\langnp1033\insrsid12529987\charrsid12529987  didn\rquote t
 see the owls swooping past in broad daylight, though people down in the street did; they pointed and gazed open-mouthed as owl after owl sped over\-
head. Most of them had never seen an owl even at nighttime. Mr. Dursley, however, had a perfectly normal, owl-free morning. He yelled at five different people. He made several important tele\-
phone calls and shouted a bit more. He was in a very good mood until lunchtime, when he thought he\rquote d stretch his legs and walk across the road to buy himself a bun from the bakery.
\par He\rquote d forgotten all about the people in cloaks until he passed a group of them next to the baker\rquote s. He eyed them angrily as he passed. He didn\rquote 
t know why, but they made him uneasy. This bunch were whispering excitedly, too, and he couldn\rquote t see a sin
gle collecting tin. It was on his way back past them, clutching a large doughnut in a bag, that he caught a few words of what they were saying.
\par \'93The Potters, that\rquote s right, that\rquote s what I heard \emdash \'94
\par \'93\emdash  yes, their son, Harry \emdash \'94
\par Mr. Dursley stopped dead. Fear flooded him. He looked back at the whisperers as if he wanted to say something to them, but thought better of it.
\par He dashed back across the road, hurried up to his office, snapped at his secretary not to disturb him, seized his telephone, and had almost fini
shed dialing his home number when he changed his mind. He put the receiver back down and stroked his mustache, thinking }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang1033\langfe3081\langnp1033\insrsid12007620 \'85}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang1033\langfe3081\langnp1033\insrsid12529987\charrsid12529987  no, he was being stupid. Potter wasn\rquote t such an unusual name. He was sure there were lots of people called Pot\-ter who had a son called Harry. Come to think of it, he wasn\rquote 
t even sure his nephew }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\lang1033\langfe3081\langnp1033\insrsid12529987\charrsid12529987 was}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang1033\langfe3081\langnp1033\insrsid12529987\charrsid12529987  called Harry. He\rquote 
d never even seen the boy. It might have been {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Harvey{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Or Harold. There was no point in wor\-
rying Mrs. Dursley; she always got so upset at any mention of her sister. He didn\rquote t blame her \emdash  if }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\lang1033\langfe3081\langnp1033\insrsid12529987\charrsid12529987 he\rquote d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang1033\langfe3081\langnp1033\insrsid12529987\charrsid12529987  had}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\lang1033\langfe3081\langnp1033\insrsid12529987\charrsid12529987  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang1033\langfe3081\langnp1033\insrsid12529987\charrsid12529987 a sister like that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang1033\langfe3081\langnp1033\insrsid12007620 \'85}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang1033\langfe3081\langnp1033\insrsid12529987\charrsid12529987  but all the same, those people in cloaks }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang1033\langfe3081\langnp1033\insrsid12007620 \'85}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang1033\langfe3081\langnp1033\insrsid12529987\charrsid12529987 
\par He found it a lot harder to concentrate on drills that afternoon and when he left the building at five o\rquote clock, he was still so worried that he walked straight into someone just outside the door.
\par \'93Sorry,\'94 he grunted, as the tiny old man stumbled and almost fell. It was a few seconds before Mr. Dursley realized that the man was wearing a violet cloak. He didn\rquote t seem at all upset at being al\-most knocked to the ground. On 
the contrary, his face split into a wide smile and he said in a squeaky voice that made passersby stare, \'93Don\rquote t be sorry, my dear sir, for nothing could upset me today! Re\-joice, for You-Know-Who has gone at last! Even Muggles like your\-
self should be celebrating, this happy, happy day!\'94
\par And the old man hugged Mr. Dursley around the middle and walked off.
\par Mr. Dursley stood rooted to the spot. He had been hugged by a complete stranger. He also thought he had been called a Muggle, whatever that was. He was ra
ttled. He hurried to his car and set off for home, hoping he was imagining things, which he had never hoped before, because he didn\rquote t approve of imagination.
\par As he pulled into the driveway of number four, the first thing he saw \emdash  and it didn\rquote t improve his mood \emdash  was the tabby cat he\rquote 
d spotted that morning. It was now sitting on his garden wall. He was sure it was the same one; it had the same markings around its eyes.
\par \'93Shoo!\'94 said Mr. Dursley loudly.
\par The cat didn\rquote t move. It just gave him a stern look. Was this nor\-mal cat behavior? Mr. Dursley wondered. Trying to pull himself to\-gether, he let himself into the house. He was still determined not to mention anything to his wife.
\par Mrs. Dursley had had a nice, normal day. She told him over din\-ner all about Mrs. Next Door\rquote s problems with her daughter and how {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dudley{\*\xmlclose} had learned a new word (\'93Won\rquote t!\'94
). Mr. Dursley tried to act normally. When {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dudley{\*\xmlclose} had been put to bed, he went into the living room in time to catch the last report on the evening news:
\par \'93And finally, bird-watchers everywhere have reported that the nation\rquote 
s owls have been behaving very unusually today. Although owls normally hunt at night and are hardly ever seen in daylight, there have been hundreds of sightings of these birds flying in every direction s
